          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Arnold's nerve is the auricular branch of the vagus nerve that supplies the posterior wall of the ear canal. Which clinical phenomenon does this innervation explain?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hearing loss following ear syringing</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hearing loss after syringing results from mechanical trauma or water-related damage, not from vagal innervation of the canal.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Coughing triggered during syringing of the ear canal</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Arnold's nerve shares its vagal origin with branches supplying the larynx and bronchi. Stimulating the ear canal can therefore trigger the cough reflex — the ear-cough reflex.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Referred pain in the ear from a mandibular fracture</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Referred pain from the mandible involves the auriculotemporal nerve (CN V₃), not Arnold's nerve (CN X).</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Loss of sensation over the lobule of the ear</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The lobule is supplied by the greater auricular nerve (C2, C3), not by Arnold's nerve.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Arnold's nerve is the auricular branch of the vagus (CN X). Because it shares central connections with branches supplying the larynx and bronchi, stimulating the ear canal can trigger coughing — the ear-cough reflex."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Arnold's nerve (auricular branch of CN X) innervates the posterior wall of the ear canal. Its vagal origin explains both the ear-cough reflex and referred otalgia from disease of the larynx, oesophagus, or heart."
                }
              ],
