          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During myringotomy, the incision is made in the anteroinferior quadrant of the tympanic membrane. What is the primary anatomical reason for choosing this site?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The pars flaccida is thinnest here, allowing easier incision</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The pars flaccida (Shrapnell's membrane) is in the posterosuperior part of the tympanic membrane, not the anteroinferior quadrant.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It lies farthest from the ossicles, facial nerve, chorda tympani, and round window</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The anteroinferior quadrant is the safest site because it is farthest from the ossicular chain, the facial nerve, the chorda tympani nerve, and the round window.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The internal carotid artery behind this quadrant provides haemostatic tamponade</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The internal carotid artery runs deep to the anterior wall of the middle ear. Its proximity is a hazard to be avoided, not a surgical advantage.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The handle of the malleus crosses this quadrant, providing a reliable landmark</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The handle of the malleus crosses the tympanic membrane diagonally from above and is a structure to be avoided during incision, not a reason for choosing this site.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The anteroinferior quadrant is chosen because it lies farthest from the ossicular chain, the facial nerve, the chorda tympani nerve, and the round window — making it the safest site for incision through the tympanic membrane."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "The anteroinferior quadrant avoids all vulnerable structures — the ossicular chain, the facial nerve, the chorda tympani, and the round window. A grommet is then inserted to maintain drainage and equalise middle ear pressure."
                }
              ],
